  "answer": "The forbidden case is not established as contradictory because the mechanism posits a supply-side shock that disrupts the flow of new tin into the interdependent gift-exchange economy, not that every physical gram of tin instantly vanished. Abundant tin stockpiles in destruction layers are fully consistent with a scenario where the supply chain broke down: palaces could hoard existing tin as a strategic resource precisely because new supplies were cut off, yet the broader systemic collapse of the reciprocal trade network—and the resulting loss of elite monopoly on finished weaponry and the debasement of in-kind currency—still delegitimized palace authority. The presence of stockpiles does not demonstrate that tin remained economically accessible or circulating in the network; it may instead reflect a failed attempt to control a suddenly scarce and non-renewing resource, which is exactly the kind of hoarding behavior a supply shock predicts. The forbidden case therefore does not falsify the mechanism, because the mechanism’s causal driver is the interruption of supply and the collapse of the distribution system, not the absolute absence of tin atoms at every site."
